snippet.textDisplay:
If you make somewhere above $35,000 a year after taxes, then this is possible as a budget listing--all things considered, even the saffron.

But if you're a college student--and the only thing you can afford is the dollar menu at McDonald's--then this video is not college-budget friendly.

It's all about your personal budgeting and money skills in the end... not because Gordon Ramsey is a multi-millionaire.

snippet.textDisplay:
So heres an actual budget meal idea lmao:
- fry up whatever veggies you have in a frying pan. I usually have onions and carrots or frozen veg from the dollar store. But whatever you have is great.
- cook up some instant ramen, discard or save the flavor packet as we will not need it
-make a sauce with peanut butter (crunchy is ideal), soy sauce and sriracha (or anything spicy rly). U can always get fancy and add chili flakes, a squeeze of lime, tamarind paste or some sesame oil if you want but we tryna keep it cheap as possible out here.
-add cooked ramen to the pan along with the sauce
-fry until ideal thickness/friedness has been reached

Note that u can always use whatever protein you want with it aside from just the pb. I use tofu or edamame if I happen to have it which I usually dont. Peanuts are chill too.

snippet.textDisplay: lamb, saffron, and prawns are not budget ingredients Gordon. That little bowl of saffron you had sitting out would cost a few hundred bucks where I live. Maybe it's cheaper in the UK? Lamb here is about $10/lb and a bag of frozen prawns runs around $20. I had red lentils for dinner tonight with caramelized onions and turmeric rice. THAT's a budget meal. Lentils=$0.50, Rice=$1, onion=$0.69 and the turmeric comes from my local dollar store so it costs pennies to use. Budget to me means spending less than $5.

snippet.textDisplay: I can’t eat lamb. Why? Because the butcher ewes. Old ewes. When they’re cooking I can smell wool. If you’ve never raised sheep you wouldn’t know that smell. It’s like dirty wet wool. Blah. Those steaks show me that was a big animal. Over a year old and I won’t eat it. So I don’t, won’t eat lamb. Too bad actually. We sold baby lambs for Easter, now those smelled sweet. Ewes and bulls stink. Sorry. Same thing when they sell old cows and bulls. you wouldn’t notice if you’ve never butchered your own. I know. here’s a hint, if you’re chewing, and chewing, it’s dry and tough, it’s old. Don’t eat it! Take it back to the store and get you’re money back! Also, if you use a butcher, walk your meat and mark it with your own mark. That means from the farmer. a if your eating a 1,000 dressed beef.it a damn cow or bull. It should weight anywhere from 500 to 600 lbs dressed. Dressed me as head, tail, insides all removed. Pigs about 300 lbs. You’re a fabulous, great chef! Just a little education. I love food!

snippet.textDisplay:
For the people splurting out random crap about saffron and lamb. If you spend 30 dollars on Saffron, it will last you literally the entire year feeding a family of 6. On a cost per meal analysis, that is EXTREMELY cheap. As for referencing lamb. Not everyone lives in the U.S lol. Lamb is dirt cheap over where he's at. It's near the equivalent, if not cheaper, of getting beef in Texas/Nebraska. Vanilla is also fairly cheap in relation to how much of it you use. A few specks of a bean ((literally a few specks of it)) can season an entire pot of food. Even with liberal use it'll last you a good 6 months.

Mackeral: Extremely cheap fish, arguably one of the healthiest + sustainable too.

Prawn+ pork: Also dirt cheap

Avocado: Spend 4 dollars for 2 of them in land locked zones. 2 avocados will last around a week. They're also very filling and jam packed with nutrients. Can very easily meal prep 7 different meals with just two avocados.

Star Anise: You can plop one, maybe even two star anise into a GIANT POT THAT WILL FEED YOU FOR 3+ WEEKS.


All in all, I can say with 100% confidence that Ramsay's meals were exceptionally cheap + on the healthy end . . . which is unique in the world of cheap food.


You guys spend more on cheap cigarettes + random gas station garbage a month than you would utilizing the techniques he demonstrated here.
